english:
  title: Preface to the Chronological Tables of Successive Dynasties
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Human wisdom falters when the mind grows confused, and affairs reach their limit when thought becomes shallow. To seek a day without flaw, a single matter without fault—this cannot be achieved. How much less so when we must span the vast breadth of heaven and earth, the distant depths of past and present?

    Whatever we undertake, if we examine it against what has gone before without contradiction, and project it into what is to come with consistency, only those whose wisdom and reflection surpass the common multitude can accomplish this. One day, my fellow examination-year companion, Hsu Kang-chung of Ta-cheng, brought me his five fascicules of Chronological Tables of Successive Dynasties and asked me to write a preface. As for the original intent of his compilation, Master Hsu has already explained it in detail. To expand further and offer excessive praise would be presumptuous—like striking a paper drum at the Thunder Gate. Who am I to add such folly?

    I observe that when Confucius composed the Spring and Autumn Annals, he necessarily noted the year at the beginning of each event, incorporating the sixty-year cycle to establish the annalistic method. Ssu-ma Ch'ien and Pan Ku later transformed this annalistic form into tables, biographies, records, and treatises, yet their chronological tables and basic records still retained the spirit of the annalistic approach. For history depends upon having a main framework with subordinate details properly arranged.

    Now this book extends from the first year of Emperor K'u above to the eighteenth year of the Ming Cheng-hua reign below—spanning more than three thousand eight hundred years. Above, the sixty-year cycles are arrayed in endless circulation; below, the years are noted in perpetual succession. At first glance, it seems to offer nothing for investigation. Yet when one examines ancient and modern times through the lens of these cycles, suddenly the succession of emperors, kings, and nobles becomes clear; the alternation of order and chaos, rise and fall, appears before one's eyes; the mechanisms of unity and division, the traces of territorial expansion and contraction, all become luminous and plain.

    Sometimes heavenly patterns validate human affairs; sometimes human affairs validate heavenly patterns. Truly, the residual wisdom of Shao Tzu's supreme ordering of the world is contained herein. The master's wisdom and reflection extend deep and far. The reader of history, through this work, awakens to contemplation of past and present, finding his thoughts grounded in evidence, his understanding harmonious and unconfused—as one who holds the balance sees weight and lightness determine themselves, or who lights the magic horn sees all mysteries revealed. There is no need to parse each line and scrutinize each character to grasp its essence.

    Thus, though we say we examine the past without contradiction and project into the future with consistency, there is no shame in this claim. As time continues forward, how many cycles must yet pass? How many generations must yet come? How many ages of flourishing? How many eras of hardship? Beyond all that, as heaven and earth endure and all time unfolds, so too shall this method continue without end.

    Ah, the master's vast knowledge and discerning learning—truly, through this very work one may glimpse but a fraction of his excellence.
  footnotes:
    - The Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches (六甲) form a sixty-year cycle used in traditional East Asian chronology and divination.
    - The Spring and Autumn Annals (春秋) is the foundational chronicle traditionally attributed to Confucius.
    - Shao Tzu's Supreme Ordering of the World (皇極經世書) is a cosmological and historical work by the Song philosopher Shao Yung (邵雍).
    - The 'magic horn' (犀角) refers to a rhinoceros horn traditionally believed in East Asian lore to reveal supernatural phenomena when burned.
